[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon Kinesis Data Streams, AWS Lambda, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon S3, Amazon API Gateway, AWS Step Functions, Amazon CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `kinesis:GetRecords`, `kinesis:PutRecord`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `states:StartExecution`, `logs:CreateLogGroup` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (required: ICU data is PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; Kinesis: server-side encryption with KMS; SageMaker: KMS for model artifacts and endpoint data; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: all components in VPC with private subnets. VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker, Kinesis, CloudWatch Logs. No internet egress for inference path. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls. Critical for audit trail of who accessed scores and when. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Data Requirements** | Minimum 2-3 years of historical ICU data with outcomes. At least 5,000-10,000 ICU admissions for initial training. Must include patients who survived AND patients who died (class balance matters). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Kinesis: ~$500/month (2 shards, 30-bed ICU). SageMaker endpoint: ~$2,000-$5,000/month (ml.m5.xlarge with auto-scaling). DynamoDB: ~$200/month (on-demand). Lambda: ~$100/month. Training jobs: ~$500-$2,000 per retrain cycle (monthly). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams** | Real-time ingestion of vitals, labs, medications, and assessments |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Compute temporal features on each new data arrival |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Low-latency feature store for current patient state vectors |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Model training (GPU), real-time inference endpoint, model registry |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Training data, model artifacts, calibration sets, audit logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | REST API for clinical applications to query scores |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrate retraining pipeline with approval gates |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Performance monitoring, drift detection, clinical alerting |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest and in transit |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-examples`](https://github.com/aws/amazon-sagemaker-examples): Comprehensive SageMaker examples including real-time inference endpoints and model monitoring
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-immersion-day`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-sagemaker-immersion-day): Hands-on workshops covering training, deployment, and monitoring patterns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`real-time-analytics-spark-streaming`](https://github.com/aws-samples/real-time-analytics-spark-streaming): Real-time streaming analytics patterns applicable to clinical data pipelines
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Ingest clinical data streams.** ICU data arrives from multiple source systems at different frequencies. Bedside monitors push vitals every few seconds. Lab results arrive every few hours. Medication administrations are logged as they happen. All of these streams must be captured, ordered, and made available for feature computation. The key design choice is partitioning by patient ID so that all data for a single patient flows through the same processing path in order. Without this ordering guarantee, you might compute features using a lab result that arrived before the vital signs that preceded it chronologically. Skip this step and you have no data to score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION ingest_clinical_event(event):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Each clinical event arrives with a patient identifier, timestamp,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // event type (vital, lab, medication, assessment), and the actual values.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // We route it to a stream partitioned by patient ID to maintain ordering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     record = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id:   event.patient_id,          // ICU patient identifier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         timestamp:    event.timestamp,            // when this measurement was taken
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         event_type:   event.type,                 // "vital", "lab", "medication", "assessment"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         source:       event.source_system,        // which system sent this (monitor, LIS, eMAR)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         values:       event.measurements          // the actual data (HR=110, SBP=85, etc.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Send to the streaming ingestion layer, partitioned by patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Partition key = patient_id ensures all data for one patient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // is processed in order by downstream consumers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     send record to stream with partition_key = event.patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN success
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Compute temporal features.** Raw clinical values are not what the model consumes. The model needs engineered features that capture temporal patterns: trends, variability, extremes, and rates of change over multiple time windows. Each time a new data point arrives, the feature computation updates the relevant aggregations. This is where domain expertise lives. A heart rate of 110 is mildly concerning. A heart rate that went from 70 to 110 over 2 hours while blood pressure dropped from 120 to 85 is an emergency. The features must capture these relationships. Skip this step and the model sees only snapshots, not trajectories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION compute_features(patient_id, new_event):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Retrieve the patient's current feature state from the feature store.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This contains all previously computed aggregations and raw recent values.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_state = get feature_state from feature_store for patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Update the relevant time series with the new data point.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Different event types update different feature groups.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF new_event.type == "vital":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_vital_features(current_state, new_event)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF new_event.type == "lab":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_lab_features(current_state, new_event)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF new_event.type == "medication":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_medication_features(current_state, new_event)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF new_event.type == "assessment":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_assessment_features(current_state, new_event)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Recompute derived features that depend on multiple data types.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Example: shock index = HR / SBP (needs both vital signs).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Example: vasopressor-adjusted MAP (needs vitals + medications).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     recompute_derived_features(current_state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute trajectory features: slopes, deltas, variability over windows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     compute_temporal_aggregations(current_state, windows=[6h, 12h, 24h, 48h])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write the updated feature vector back to the feature store.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write current_state to feature_store for patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN current_state
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION compute_temporal_aggregations(state, windows):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For each clinical variable, compute statistics over each time window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // These capture "what's been happening" not just "what's happening now."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each variable in [heart_rate, sbp, dbp, map, spo2, resp_rate, temperature,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                           lactate, creatinine, bilirubin, platelets, wbc, pao2_fio2]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each window in windows:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             recent_values = get values for variable within window from state.history
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.features[variable + "_mean_" + window]   = mean(recent_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.features[variable + "_min_" + window]    = min(recent_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.features[variable + "_max_" + window]    = max(recent_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.features[variable + "_std_" + window]    = std_deviation(recent_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.features[variable + "_slope_" + window]  = linear_slope(recent_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.features[variable + "_last"]             = most_recent(recent_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.features[variable + "_hours_since"]      = hours_since_last(recent_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Treatment intensity features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.features["vasopressor_count"]       = count active vasopressors
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.features["norepinephrine_equiv"]    = total vasopressor dose in NE equivalents
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.features["fio2_current"]            = current FiO2 setting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.features["peep_current"]            = current PEEP setting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.features["ventilator_mode"]         = encoded ventilator mode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.features["rrt_active"]              = is renal replacement therapy running (0/1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Missingness features (how much clinical attention is this patient getting?)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.features["labs_ordered_24h"]        = count of lab orders in last 24 hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.features["vital_frequency_1h"]      = count of vital measurements in last hour
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.features["nursing_assessments_12h"] = count of nursing notes in last 12 hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Score the patient.** With the feature vector current, invoke the mortality prediction model. The model produces a raw score (logit or probability) that represents the patient's mortality risk. This happens on a schedule (every 15-60 minutes) or can be triggered by significant clinical events (new critical lab result, vasopressor initiation). The raw score is not yet ready for clinical use; it needs calibration. But this step is where the core prediction happens. Skip it and you have features with no prediction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION score_patient(patient_id):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Retrieve the current feature vector for this patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     feature_vector = get features from feature_store for patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate that the feature vector is fresh enough to score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If the most recent data is more than 2 hours old, the score is stale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This can happen if a data pipeline is down or the patient was just admitted.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF feature_vector.last_updated > 2 hours ago:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN { status: "stale", reason: "Feature data older than 2 hours" }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check minimum data requirements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The model needs at least some vital signs and basic labs to produce
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // a meaningful prediction. Without them, the uncertainty is too high.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF feature_vector.hours_since_admission < 4:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN { status: "insufficient_data", reason: "Less than 4 hours of ICU data" }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Invoke the model endpoint with the feature vector.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The model returns a raw mortality probability and feature importances.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     raw_prediction = call model_endpoint with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features = feature_vector.to_array()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The raw output includes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - mortality_probability: raw model output (before calibration)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - feature_importances: which features drove this prediction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - prediction_horizon: what time window this covers (24h, 48h, 7d)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN raw_prediction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Calibrate the prediction.** The raw model output is not a well-calibrated probability. Neural networks and gradient-boosted models are notoriously overconfident or underconfident depending on the training regime. The calibration layer maps raw scores to honest probabilities using a function learned on a held-out calibration dataset. This layer is retrained more frequently than the base model (monthly vs. quarterly) because calibration can drift as the patient population or treatment patterns change. Skip this step and clinicians will make decisions based on probabilities that don't mean what they claim to mean.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION calibrate_prediction(raw_prediction, patient_demographics):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply post-hoc calibration to convert raw model output
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // into a well-calibrated probability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Select the appropriate calibration function based on patient subgroup.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // We maintain separate calibration curves for key subgroups because
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // a single calibration function may not be accurate across all populations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgroup = determine_calibration_subgroup(patient_demographics)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Subgroups might be: age brackets, primary diagnosis category,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // surgical vs. medical ICU, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     calibration_function = load calibration_model for subgroup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply calibration. This is typically isotonic regression or Platt scaling
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // fitted on a recent holdout dataset.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     calibrated_probability = calibration_function.transform(raw_prediction.mortality_probability)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute confidence interval using the calibration model's uncertainty.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Wider intervals = less certain. This is critical for clinical communication.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     confidence_interval = compute_confidence_bounds(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         calibrated_probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         calibration_function.uncertainty,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         confidence_level = 0.80   // 80% CI: "we're 80% sure the true risk is in this range"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mortality_24h:     calibrated_probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         confidence_lower:  confidence_interval.lower,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         confidence_upper:  confidence_interval.upper,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         calibration_group: subgroup,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model_version:     current_model_version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         scored_at:         current_timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Present to clinicians with context.** A bare probability is not clinically useful. Clinicians need context: what's driving the score, how has it changed, and how does this patient compare to similar patients. This step assembles the clinical display package that integrates into the EHR or a dedicated dashboard. The presentation must include uncertainty bounds, trend information, and explicit caveats about what the score does and does not mean. Skip this step and you have a number that no one trusts or uses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION build_clinical_display(patient_id, calibrated_score, raw_prediction):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Assemble the full clinical context for score presentation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Get score history for trend display.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     score_history = get last 48 hours of scores for patient_id from audit_log
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Identify the top contributing features (what's driving this score).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Clinicians need to understand WHY the score is what it is.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     top_factors = extract top 5 features from raw_prediction.feature_importances
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Translate feature names to clinical language:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "norepinephrine_equiv" -> "Vasopressor dose (norepinephrine equivalents)"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "lactate_slope_6h" -> "Lactate trend over last 6 hours"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     clinical_factors = translate_to_clinical_language(top_factors)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute trend: is the patient getting better or worse?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF length(score_history) >= 2:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         trend = compute_trend(score_history)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // trend = "improving", "stable", "worsening", or "rapidly_worsening"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         trend = "insufficient_history"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Build the display object.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     display = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id:          patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         current_score:       calibrated_score.mortality_24h,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         confidence_interval: [calibrated_score.confidence_lower,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                               calibrated_score.confidence_upper],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         trend:               trend,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         trend_description:   describe_trend(trend, score_history),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         top_factors:         clinical_factors,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         score_history:       score_history,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model_version:       calibrated_score.model_version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         last_updated:        calibrated_score.scored_at,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         caveats: [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "This score reflects statistical patterns and does not account for all clinical context.",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "Treatment decisions should never be based solely on this score.",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "Score assumes current treatment continues unchanged.",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "Discuss with the care team before using in goals-of-care conversations."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Log this score presentation for audit purposes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     log_score_presentation(patient_id, display, requesting_user)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN display
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Log outcomes and detect drift.** The system must track what actually happens to patients and compare it to what was predicted. This serves two purposes: monitoring model performance in real time (detecting when the model starts getting worse) and accumulating data for the next retraining cycle. Outcome tracking must handle the complexity of ICU dispositions: discharge alive, in-hospital death, transition to comfort care (which is different from "natural" death), transfer to another facility (outcome unknown). Skip this step and you'll never know if your model is degrading until a clinician complains.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION track_outcome(patient_id, disposition):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Called when a patient leaves the ICU (discharge, death, transfer).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Retrieve all predictions made for this patient during their stay.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_predictions = get predictions for patient_id from audit_log
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Determine the actual outcome for comparison.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     actual_outcome = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         survived_to_discharge: disposition.type == "discharge_alive",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         died_in_hospital:      disposition.type == "death",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         comfort_care:          disposition.type == "comfort_care_transition",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         transferred:           disposition.type == "transfer_out",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         icu_los_hours:         disposition.icu_length_of_stay,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hospital_los_hours:    disposition.hospital_length_of_stay
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For each prediction, compute the prediction error.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each prediction in all_predictions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         error = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             predicted_mortality: prediction.mortality_24h,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             actual_died_within_24h: did_patient_die_within(24h, prediction.scored_at),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             prediction_age_hours: hours_between(prediction.scored_at, disposition.time),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             comfort_care_flag: actual_outcome.comfort_care
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Flag comfort care cases: these are ambiguous for model evaluation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // because death was influenced by treatment withdrawal decision
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         store error in model_performance_log
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check for calibration drift.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compare recent prediction accuracy to expected calibration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     recent_errors = get last 100 outcomes from model_performance_log
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     calibration_drift = compute_calibration_drift(recent_errors)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF calibration_drift > DRIFT_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         trigger alert: "Model calibration has drifted. Review and consider recalibration."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN actual_outcome
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter07.09-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample output for a single patient scoring cycle:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "patient_id": "ICU-2026-04821",
